      "comment_id" : 98093069,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "What if I want to get all the numbers (or any other character/string) but the ones preceded by a given string: e.g.: <code>String s = &quot;foo123 bar45 foo1 bar7&quot;</code>. I&#39;d like to get: 45 and 7. This re doesn&#39;t work properly: <code>(?&lt;!foo)\\d+</code>"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 10989831,
        "reputation" : 428,
        "user_id" : 8074234,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 0,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/gbwSx.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Freelensia",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8074234/freelensia"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1621765354,
      "post_id" : 9306228,
      "comment_id" : 119589355,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Thanks for this. However this only match the first instance. How do I match all instances of bar not proceeded by foo? I tried \\w*(?&lt;!foo)barg but of course that is not right. Sorry I am quite new to Regex."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1089021,
      "reputation" : 6591,
      "user_id" : 1084078,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4130df70b9cc58e16add6dbb91d9ecf6?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Adam Rofer",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1084078/adam-rofer"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 524,
    "last_activity_date" : 1497500118,
    "last_edit_date" : 1497500118,
    "creation_date" : 1329371576,
    "answer_id" : 9306228,
    "question_id" : 9306202,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You want to use <code>negative lookbehind</code> like this: </p>\n\n<pre><code>\\w*(?&lt;!foo)bar\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Where <code>(?&lt;!x)</code> means \"only if it doesn't have \"x\" before this point\".</p>\n\n<p>See <a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/lookaround.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Regular Expressions - Lookaround</a> for more information.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Edit</strong>: added the <code>\\w*</code> to capture the characters before (e.g. \"beach\").</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 7089168,
      "reputation" : 164725,
      "user_id" : 5424988,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/26fnQYyM.webp?s=256",
      "display_name" : "The fourth bird",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5424988/the-fourth-bird"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1620250942,
    "last_edit_date" : 1620250942,
    "creation_date" : 1620249713,
    "answer_id" : 67408886,
    "question_id" : 9306202,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Another option is to first match optional word characters followed by <code>bar</code>, and when that has matched check what is directly to the left is not <code>foobar</code>.</p>\n<p>The lookbehind assertion will run after matching <code>bar</code> first.</p>\n<pre><code>\\w*bar(?&lt;!foobar)\n</code></pre>\n<ul>\n<li><code>\\w*</code> Match 0+ word characters</li>\n<li><code>bar</code> Match literally</li>\n<li><code>(?&lt;!foobar)</code> Negative lookbehind, assert from the current position <code>foobar</code> is not directly to the left.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://regex101.com/r/6Fhmlc/1\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Regex demo</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 457657,
      "reputation" : 2246,
      "user_id" : 857113,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/CZf0ccrk.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Frank Forte",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/857113/frank-forte"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1648573845,
    "creation_date" : 1648573845,
    "answer_id" : 71666187,
    "question_id" : 9306202,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In some cases, it could be easier to optionally include the preceding part, then skip those matches in a second step. For instance, to find numbers that don't start with a &quot;+&quot;:</p>\n<pre><code>if (preg_match_all('/(\\+?[0-9][0-9\\s\\-].*[0-9])/s',$text,$matches)) {\n    foreach($matches[1] as $match) {\n        if(substr($match,0,1) == '+'){\n            continue;\n        }\n        // continue processing\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>The negative look behind did not work since it would still match 2+ digits, but it would not include the first digit in the match. For instance +1234 would be returned as 234.</p>\n"
  } ],
